br>
<br>
1. The plow to named (or exp-group)<br>
You never sit at FM, therefore any bit of +manaregen helps you do additional damage, manapool is somewhat irrelevant.<br>
<br>
2. The named fight<br>
Damage is often constricted by aggro, this along with the fight being somewhat short'ish in PoP at least makes regen (and manapool) less of an issue, because you can easily unload up to aggro-limit with a lower manaregen. Due to the short time of these encounters, manapool/focus effects/crits will be somewhat more useful than regen - this of course depending on fight etc. <p><big><center><b><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=370955 target=blank>Sage Aauminki Iceblade</a><br><a href=http://www.vazaelle.dk target=blank>Caer Cadarn</a></big><br>Vazaelle Server</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sincrofashad>SincroFashad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/18/03 5:58 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The High End Wizard</span><hr size=1> Ok, yeah, that makes sense.  On the specific named fights, mana regen is largely irrelevent since the fight doesn't last long enough to unload a full bar without drawing aggro and getting the smack-down laid on you.  I assume we're not talking about the bosses of either Ssra or VT here, since those damn things have 800 zillion hit points.  Mana regen is an issue for those as well.<br>
