<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It was asserted that the disparity exsists because Veng items contribute directly to DPS, while FT itmes do not. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Hmm I'd have to see the original post to say for sure but I do not agree with this assertion and conclusion, that is, that FT items are more available because Vengeance adds directly to DPS.  While there are a great many situations where additional FT does not let you deal more damage, FT is also powerful because it does not NEED to be used for damage-- FT affects mana which is connected to ALL spells, not just nukes.<br>
<br>
However that doesn't mean there should be more Vengeance items, or that we should even look for a &quot;disparity&quot; between the two in the first place.  Melee and spellcasting are totally different.  Now.. both types have to worry about aggro, but melees have nothing at all like mana.  Actually I think it would be better to approach the issue by sharing some facts and asking you a few questions..<br>
<br>
<br>
It is relatively easy to contrive situations where a caster will be able to realize his full potential, and the flowing thought would have had zero difference in the outcome of the fight.  After major fights, ask your casters how much mana they have left.  Personally I usually wind up anywhere between 10% and 60%, but then I am not a wizard.  I would say full mana regen has only mattered on maybe half of the fights I've ever encountered..  Now I ask you:<br>
<br>
How often do you look back on a fight and think &quot;Well I guess I didn't really need the Vengeance,&quot; not counting fights where you die?  My guess is only the fights where are unable to get in melee range.<br>
<br>
How often do you look ahead to a fight <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>knowing</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that you won't use your Vengeance?  --That you might as well wear nothing at all for all the difference it will make.  My guess is even less.<br>
<br>
Now again, the point here is not to show that FT should be more common than Vengeance, to answer that question one really needs to look at each class's capabilities and loot selection as a whole, the point is that FT and Vengeance don't really give the type of benefits that are easily compareable.  In some situations, FT is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>more</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> useful than Vengeance, other situations Vengeance is clearly superior.  Casters don't need to prove that mana regen &quot;never&quot; or &quot;almost never&quot; affects dps in order to make the point that they aren't easily compareable.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'm almost ready to concede this point too, but something just nags at me when the statement that additional mana regen is essentially no use once you reach a certain level, and that level of mana regen appears to be quite low. Is wizard damage/mana seriously that hyper-efficient that you can't run oom with gear available to Ssra/Tier 2-3 plane guilds?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Ssra/Tier 2-3 plane guilds are not the ones being discussed by the original poster, and Ssra/Tier 2-3 casters probably won't generally have gobs of FT.  Flowing Thought comes in greatest quantities from Vex Thal.  6-10 can probably be achieved by normal ssra-level casters, but don't forget Aura of Battle items-- those give +ATK.  Casters also still don't have an &quot;equivalent&quot; to primal weapons.<br>
<br>
And again it is not so much the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>level</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> or even <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>level</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of play, it is the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>nature</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of the play.  It's the environment that leads to FT being severely marginalized.<br>
<br>
Also don't make the mistake of assuming that just because a caster isn't worried about mana that they are just nuking away non-stop.  There are other things that reduce nuker output..  Sometimes it's not that mana regen is so high or the mob dies fast, it's that for some reason the caster simply cannot spend his mana.  Again a clear example of this would be Wuoshi or Severilous.  If a wizard spends 75% of the time stunned he won't be spending much time nuking and his mana will go down very slowly.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As a rogue, all I can look forward to in an XP group or on a raid is dealing damage. I have a couple very minor tricks I can do, but damage is pretty much the reason to invite me. Forgive me if I'm wrong, but I see wizards the same way. I don't ask for a wizard in an XP group so I have an evac capability, I ask for em cause you nuke. I've always looked at additional mana regen as a nice, easy way to up your DPS while maintaining a steady-state of mana. I'm still not 100% sure I believe you, but I think I'll take this as my cue to shut up and color. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->You don't really need to get pouty heh...<br>
<br>
Realize Qaman is speaking from his own experience, which is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> a Ssra/Teir3 guild, he's Teir 4.  I do suspect that he takes some of his FT for granted, but probably not much.  I don't think either of us can really comment on his level of XPing.  I can tell you, though, that at my level FT can help my dps go up.  If you are talking relative to a melee, FT15 probably would account for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>more</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> than 6dps, because melee damage suffers from downtime. <p><center><br>
<font = "arial" size = 3>Goladus Mistrydia<br>
<a href = "http://www.darkblood.com">Darkblood</a></font><br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=317634"><font = "arial" size = 1>(profile)</font></a>
</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=qaman>Qaman</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 2398<br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/19/03 11:39 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The High End Wizard</span><hr size=1> &gt;What got me into this thread was the comment that KEI helps a wizard maintain damage relative to melee. I conveniently ignored that the poster was talking about a lower level wizard, and not the end-game. I wasn't totally convinced mana-regen, or additional mana regen, didn't help a wizards DPS, so I applied that statement to the end-game<br>
<br>
Yes, KEI and FT can help you maintain sustained damage relative to melee in some situations. The primary reason for this is that melee have no cap on how long they can sustain damage. If they aren't dead, they can do damage. This is not the case with casters. You are trying to compare apples and oranges, but somehow I feel you keep coming up with lemonade. But you can't just say FT raises DPS by X amount because a number of conditions have to be met before it is even effective, and if those conditions are not met, the effect is zero. At the high end, you just tend to have so much mana regen that FT kinda gets lost in the noise of the rest of the mana regen. I have roughly 6300 mana available, it takes a long time to empty that when mana is coming in at roughly 100/tick without FT which is about what I get when raiding. I will admit that in groups it can have a bit more impact though. <br>
<br>
Again though, you can't just say FT adds X DPS because it just doesn't work that way. If I fight once an hour and don't go OOM, FT has essentially no effect. Compare that to melee that picks up a better weapon or Vengeance items. Those do have an effect, even if you only fight once an hour. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=4380">Qaman</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
